To obtain uniform distributions in the marginals, we transformed marginal distributions into normalized ranks, which is a common procedure when working with copulas (
 
  52
 , 
 
  53
 ) and is the only reasonable choice if goodness of fit is to be tested appropriately (
 
  54
 ). We fit four different Archimedean copulas (Clayton, Frank, Gumbel, and Joe; see above and fig. S8) and selected the one with the best fit relying on the Bayesian Information Criterion implemented in the R package VineCopula (
 
  55
 ). Goodness of fit was tested based on the Cramér–von Mises statistic (
 
  54
 ) implemented in the R package copula (
 
  56
 ). 
 P values below 0.05 (rejecting the hypothesis that the copula is a good fit) were obtained for about 3% of the fits, which is an acceptable rate.
